			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Something I posted on our guild's message board in order to point out that wizards aren't that superior even on boss mobs:
<br />

<br />
---
<br />

<br />
On many boss encounters, you're bound more as a nuker by aggro than by maximum burst DPS or mana constraints. I thought I'd make a quick calculation to see what this means for wizards compared to nukers that don't have aggro reduction - mainly mages, but naturally druids and necros as well. Druids don't get the spellcasting subtlety AA, so they will score lower DPS per hate. We mages use a lot more rains than wizards do, for less aggro but not quite as good efficiency. This means that a mage will have a bit less hate per DPS, but I'll keep this calculation simple by just equating all kinds of nukes as far as aggro goes. The fact that crits don't count more towards aggro will also be overlooked - not a huge difference in crit percentage between wizards and mages anyway.
<br />

<br />
The comparisons will be between a mage and a wizard - both having the AA's and gear you can expect of them - and the wizard will have QD3 as well as EP leggings.
<br />

<br />
Maximum possible nuking burst DPS only using fire for a mage is slightly over 300, so the highest value to be compared will be 300 hate. For the mage, no calculation will be necessary, really - just fill up the fight with nukes as the aggro limit allows. The wizard on the other hand will alternate how much time he will spend clicking his leggings, to reach the aggro limit.
<br />

<br />
The wizard, who for simplicity only will be doing SoS, has this equation:
<br />

<br />
Base damage 2740, 0.155 average focus addition, 0.2 or something like that from crits, 4.8 seconds casting time on SoS. The number 2 is from the casting time on the concussion clicky.
<br />

<br />
Hate limit = Y
<br />
Duration in seconds of a nuking cycle + concussions = X
<br />

<br />
Y = (2740 * (1 + 0.155 + 0.2) - 400 * ( X - 4.8 ) /2 ) / X
<br />

<br />
Simplifying:
<br />

<br />
Y = (3710 - 200 * (X - 4.8) ) / X
<br />

<br />
Y = (4670 - 200X) / X
<br />

<br />
If Y is 300, X is = 9.34
<br />
If Y is 200, X is = 11.675
<br />
if Y is 100, X is ~ 15.6
<br />

<br />
SoS damage should be 3710 on average.. Hence:
<br />

<br />
With Y = 300, DPS ~ 397
<br />
With Y = 200, DPS ~ 318
<br />
With Y = 100, DPS ~ 238
<br />

<br />
The mage's DPS limit is Y + what his pet does, since the pet doesn't give any additional aggro from its damage - only a small chunk when sent to attack, and possibly also if it ganks sole focus of a mob and gets killed. A fully decked 62 water pet on a PoV mob attacking from behind is 100 DPS. The same pet on a typical PoFire mini will only do 60 on the other hand. With the typical pets we use on raids, you only get something like 50 DPS on high AC boss mobs.
<br />

<br />
Hence, assuming the pet will be kept alive, this is what a mage will be able to do under the same aggro conditions:
<br />

<br />
With Y = 300, DPS ~ 350
<br />
With Y = 200, DPS ~ 250
<br />
With Y = 100, DPS ~ 150
<br />

<br />
It really puts aggro reduction utilities like the wizard concussion spell in another perspective. Only on very aggro-sensitive mobs will it enable wizards to do way more damage than other classes. And naturally, no other class matches the maximum burst DPS of something like 550 of or wizards either.
<br />

<br />
I would say that Y is above 150 on all PoFire minis. I've even kept at 210 nuking DPS on the shadow-stepping bird without getting summoned, as well as at 190 on Fennin Ro. In the PoTime trials phase 1+2, Y seems to be in the vicinity of 250-300 for warrior tanks, I can just chain-nuke, almost never having the mob turn on me. 
<br />

<br />
---
<br />

<br />
The aggro problems facing mages in the high-end game are pretty small, wizards don't have it that much better. On boss mobs in the high-end game, the spell(not the clicky) concussion is of very little use. In fact, without EP leggings, a wizard will be outdamaged by a mage since the pet doesn't bring more aggro from damage, and the spell concussion doesn't bring hate down very quickly due to recast times. Not to mention that before a mob starts to get farmable, the fight will be slow and mana will usually become a problem for nukers unless the CH chain fails, decreasing the gap even further. 
<br />

<br />
On shorter boss fights, we can expect a 2nd or 3rd place in the DPS ranking depending on if rangers can use their TS or not, which often isn't the case. Rogues may beat us if there's an AE mana drain, but that's often dodgable. In XP groups, no other class comes close to mages. On hypothetical single-target fights lasting forever, a mage will still outdamage any other class, and he's less dependant on other people's buffs for it - just throw a pet in, nuke away, and canni back the mana when needed, though necros will naturally come very close. These other classes all have some significant weakness, however - wizards run out of steam on long fights/clearings/groups, rogues have got far less burst DPS and can't always get to backstab. Rangers can often only melee and are then lousy DPS. Necros don't do that much burst DPS either, which means they will do significantly less damage in XP groups than we do, not to mention on boss fights.
<br />

<br />
I'd say that the magician class is the best overall damage-dealer in the game, and that no fix at all is needed. The only "fix" I'd like to see is more people realizing this instead of just getting used to mages being whiners without any self-esteem.<br />_________________<br /><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=597626">Enharjaren Fenrirsbane</a> Arch convoker
<br />
The Celestial Rapture
<br />
Kane Bayle</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
