			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Just a quick note:
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">1) I think your number for wizard crit rate is low, although I don't have it written down offhand.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Commonly accepted rates for SCF1-3, SCFM1-3 and FOMM1-3 are (in order of progression):
<br />
2%, 4%, 7%, 9%, 11%, 14%, 16%, 18%, 20%
<br />

<br />
The general feeling from a number of wizards who have done recent parsing is that the original calculations for SCF and SCFM were somewhat in error (i.e. included innate crits in the calculation), and SCF and SCFM should probably be 2%, 4%, 6%, 8%, 10%, 12%.  This correction, in addition to FOMM leads to an overall crit rate of ~18% (which is in-line with a number of more recent parse results).
<br />

<br />
I should emphasize that fewer numbers have been collected on this (long-term crit parsing doesn't seem to be a priority atm), but that is the general feeling from a number of posters at Graffe's.  
<br />

<br />
Also, just FYI, innate crits do a random amount of dmg, from 1% to 55% in addition to the base dmg.  Therefore, on average, they will hit for an extra 27% dmg.  Since Innate crits occur 2% of the time, they lead to a long-term damage increase of 0.02 * 0.27 = 0.005, which is one-half of one percent.  As such, they have a negligible impact on long term dmg.  And now back to your regularly scheduled thread.   <img src="images/smiles/icon_smile.gif" alt="Smile" border="0" /> 
<br />

<br />
cheers,
<br />

<br />
Zarb.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
